# Free cooling

Free cooling is an economical method of using low external air temperatures to assist in chilling water, which can then be used for industrial processes, or [air conditioning](/Air_conditioning) systems. The [chilled water](/Chilled_water) can either be used immediately or be stored for the short‑ or long‑term. When outdoor temperatures are lower relative to indoor temperatures, this system utilizes the cool outdoor air as a free cooling source. In this manner, the system replaces the [chiller](/Chiller) in traditional [air conditioning](/Air_conditioning) systems while achieving the same cooling result. Such systems can be made for single buildings or [district cooling](/District_cooling) networks.  

---

## Operation  

This section needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) . Please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Free_cooling) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) in this section. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (May 2021) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )  

When the ambient air temperature drops to a set temperature, a modulating valve allows all or part of the chilled water to by‑pass an existing [chiller](/Chiller) and run through the free cooling system, which uses less power and uses the lower ambient air temperature to cool the water in the system. &#91;1&#93;  

This can be achieved by installing an air blast cooler with any existing [chiller](/Chiller) or on its own. During low ambient temperatures, an installation can by‑pass an existing [chiller] giving [energy savings](/Energy_savings) of up to 75 %, without compromising cooling requirements. &#91;2&#93;  

In heating, ventilation, and air conditioning ([HVAC](/HVAC)) in winter months, large commercial buildings interior spaces may need cooling, even while perimeter spaces may need heating. &#91;3&#93; Free cooling is the production of chilled water without the use of a [chiller](/Chiller), and can be used generally in the late fall, winter and early spring, in [temperate zones](/Temperate_zone). &#91;4&#93; Free cooling is not entirely free since the [chiller](/Chiller) is still operational.  

