## Methods  

•  

This section needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) . Please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Free_cooling) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) in this section. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (May 2021) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )  

Assuming that the system can utilize free cooling, there are three ways to use free cooling:  

### Strainer cycle  

The [cooling tower](/Cooling_tower) water can be directly linked into the flow through the [chilled water](/Chilled_water) circuit. If the cooling tower is open then a strainer is required to eliminate any debris that could accumulate within the tower. The cost savings are associated with the limited use of the water [chiller](/Chiller) energy. There is an increased risk of corrosion using this method.  

### Plate and frame heat exchanger  

A [heat exchanger](/Heat_exchanger) will transfer heat directly from the chilled water loop to the cooling tower loop. The exchanger keeps the cooling tower water separate from the coolant flowing through the cooling coils. The [chiller water](/Chilled_water) is thus pre‑cooled and the building is [liquid cooled](/Water_cooling). An energy savings is due to reduced [chiller](/Chiller) loading and thus a reduction in energy consumption. There is an increase in cost due to the pump needing to compensate for the pressure differences.  

### Refrigeration migration  

A valve arrangement within the water [chiller](/Chiller) opens a direct path between the [condenser](/Condenser_(heat_transfer)) and the [evaporator](/Evaporator). The relatively warm fluid in the [chiller](/Chiller) loop vaporizes the refrigerant, and the energy is carried directly to the condenser, where it is cooled and condensed by the water from the cooling tower. &#91;3&#93; This method is driven by the idea that the refrigerant tends to move towards the coldest point in a refrigeration circuit. The cost savings associated with this method are due to the compressor's inactivity, since the blower, fans and pumps are all operational.  

